				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">On the NES, 8x16 pixel sprites already index all 512 tiles.
<br />
<br />As for backgrounds, there are <em>ten</em> bits available for indexing a tile. The PPU could have switched tile banks based on bits from attribute value. For example, it could have provided two banks: one for attributes 0 and 1 and another for attributes 2 and 3. Under such a system, blatant recolors like <a href="http://www.destructoid.com/blogs/Jordan+Grim+Devore/the-bushes-in-smb-are-actually-green-colored-clouds-and-other-crazy-facts-67302.phtml" class="postlink">SMB1's cloud bushes</a> might be more difficult, but it would open up more possibilities for tiles. Nintendo ended up not making the PPU do that, but it's possible for a mapper to do that by watching attribute fetches.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
